          Post-construction cleaning costs more than regular cleaning because it takes more time, more specialized equipment, and more expertise. Here's what Birmingham-area homeowners typically pay:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">By Square Footage</h3>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li><strong>Single room renovation:</strong> $200–$400</li>
          <li><strong>Kitchen or bathroom remodel:</strong> $300–$600</li>
          <li><strong>Multiple room renovation:</strong> $400–$800</li>
          <li><strong>Whole house (2,000-3,000 sq ft):</strong> $800–$1,500</li>
          <li><strong>Large homes (3,500+ sq ft):</strong> $1,200–$2,500</li>
          <li><strong>New construction:</strong> $0.15–$0.30 per square foot</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Factors That Increase Cost</h3>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>Extent of construction work</li>
          <li>Type of materials involved (drywall, tile, hardwood)</li>
          <li>Condition contractor left the site</li>
          <li>Home's age and architectural complexity</li>
          <li>Whether dust mitigation was used during construction</li>
          <li>Access challenges (high ceilings, difficult corners)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Timing: When to Schedule Post-Construction Cleaning</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Timing matters. Schedule too early and you'll need to clean again. Wait too long and dust sets in permanently.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Ideal Sequence</h3>

        <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li><strong>All construction complete:</strong> Including punch list items, touch-up paint, final inspections</li>
          <li><strong>HVAC running:</strong> So you can address air handling before final clean</li>
          <li><strong>Before furniture moves in:</strong> Easier access, nothing to work around</li>
          <li><strong>Before flooring protection is removed:</strong> In some cases, final floor cleaning happens last</li>
        </ol>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Coordinate with your contractor on timing. Some include a basic clean in their scope; professional post-construction cleaning should happen after that.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">What to Ask Your Contractor</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Before your renovation starts, clarify cleaning expectations:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li><strong>"What cleaning is included in your scope?"</strong> Most contractors include rough cleaning, not final.</li>
          <li><strong>"Will you use dust barriers?"</strong> Plastic sheeting to contain dust to work areas saves significant cleanup later.</li>
          <li><strong>"What's your debris removal process?"</strong> Will they haul away all construction waste?</li>
          <li><strong>"Will you seal HVAC vents during work?"</strong> Prevents dust from entering your entire system.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Protecting Your Investment</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          You just invested significantly in your Birmingham home. A quality renovation in Mountain Brook or Vestavia Hills represents serious money. Proper post-construction cleaning protects that investment by:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>Removing particles that can scratch new surfaces</li>
          <li>Preventing dust from embedding in new finishes</li>
          <li>Clearing debris from mechanical systems</li>
          <li>Allowing you to actually enjoy your new space</li>
        </ul>

